Create src/app.ts — the main SPA entry that ties together api, router, and DOM. Use EXACTLY these imports (relative paths include `.js` so the unbundled ESM output resolves in the browser): `import { ApiClient } from './api.js'; import type { BrowseResult, FileEntry, SearchResult } from './api.js'; import { parseHash, getCurrentRoute, subscribe, toBrowseHash, toSearchHash, navigate } from './router.js'; import { formatBytes, normalizeRelativePath, joinPath, parentPath, basename, formatDate } from './format.js';`. Keep a module-level `const api = new ApiClient();`.

Export `function startApp(root: HTMLElement): void` that builds, inside `root`: (1) a trigger `<button class="trigger">Browse Files</button>`; (2) a native `<dialog class="browser-dialog">` containing a header (a title span + a close `<button class="btn">Close</button>`), a toolbar (a `.breadcrumb` container, a search `<input type="text" placeholder="Search...">` + a `<button class="btn">Search</button>`, and an upload control: a `<label class="btn">Upload<input type="file" hidden multiple></label>`), a `<div class="results"></div>` results container, and a `<footer class="status"></footer>`. Wire trigger click -> `dialog.showModal()` and close click -> `dialog.close()`. Store references to the elements you need to update.

Rendering: an `async function render(): Promise<void>` that reads `const route = getCurrentRoute();`, clears/disables as needed, then: if `route.view === 'browse'` call `const result = await api.browse(normalizeRelativePath(route.path));` and `renderBrowse(result, route);`; if `route.view === 'search'` call `const result = await api.search(route.query, normalizeRelativePath(route.path));` and `renderSearch(result, route);`. On error show a short error text in `.results`. Update the breadcrumb (clickable segments that call `navigate(toBrowseHash(...))`) and the `.status` footer (e.g. `N folders, M files, total S` using formatBytes) for browse results; for search show `R results for "q"`.

`renderBrowse(result: BrowseResult, route: Route)`: build a `<table>` with header Name | Size | Modified | Actions, appended to `.results`. If `result.parent !== null` add a `..` row whose Name click calls `navigate(toBrowseHash(result.parent))`. For each entry: directories get a Name that is a link navigating to `toBrowseHash(entry.path)`; files get Name text. Size column shows formatBytes(entry.size) for files and `—` for folders; Modified column shows formatDate(entry.lastModified). Actions column: for files a Download action (an `<a class="btn" href={api.downloadUrl(entry.path)} download={entry.name}>Download</a>`); for both files and folders: Delete (if `window.confirm('Delete "' + entry.name + '"?')`) then `await api.delete(entry.path)` then `render()`), Move (destination = `window.prompt('Move to relative destination path:', entry.path)`; if non-null normalize and `await api.move(entry.path, dest)` then `render()`), Copy (same pattern with `api.copy`). Use `document.createElement` + `textContent` for all user-controlled strings (folder/file names) to avoid HTML injection.

`renderSearch(result: SearchResult, route: Route)`: build a `<table>` listing results (Name, Path, Size, Modified) where clicking a directory Name navigates to `toBrowseHash(entry.path)` and clicking a file Name opens `api.downloadUrl(entry.path)`.

Toolbar handlers: the Search button (and pressing Enter in the search input) calls `navigate(toSearchHash(searchInput.value.trim(), normalizeRelativePath(currentPath)))`. The upload input `change` handler iterates `input.files`, `await api.upload(currentBrowsePath, file)` for each, clears the input, then `render()` to refresh.

At the end of startApp, call `subscribe(render)` and `render()`. At the very bottom of the file add the bootstrap (guarded so the module is importable in tests without a DOM): `const root = document.getElementById('app'); if (root) { startApp(root); }`. Keep functions small and prefer pure DOM-builder helpers you can export (e.g. export `renderBrowse` and `renderSearch`) so they can be exercised in happy-dom tests. Verify: `npm run build` compiles and emits wwwroot/dist/app.js (plus api.js, router.js, format.js) with no errors; `npm test` passes. Then, once the backend and index.html exist: `npm run build && dotnet run --project TestProject.csproj`, open the HTTPS URL, click Browse Files, and confirm the dialog lists the Home directory with working navigation/search/upload/download/delete/move/copy.

